description:
Replace all 13 .spawn() call sites in crates/springfield/tests/integration.rs with ChildGuard::spawn().

Currently these tests spawn sgf via .spawn(), get the PID, do test work (assertions, signal sends), then call .wait_with_output(). If any assertion panics before .wait_with_output(), the Child is dropped without cleanup and the sgf process (plus its mock ralph descendants) leak.

## Pattern

Before:
  let child = sgf_cmd(tmp.path()).stdout(Stdio::piped()).stderr(Stdio::piped())
      .spawn().expect("spawn sgf");
  let pid = nix::unistd::Pid::from_raw(child.id() as i32);
  // ... assertions that might panic ...
  let output = child.wait_with_output().expect("wait");

After:
  let mut guard = ChildGuard::spawn(
      sgf_cmd(tmp.path()).stdout(Stdio::piped()).stderr(Stdio::piped())
  ).expect("spawn sgf");
  let pid = nix::unistd::Pid::from_raw(guard.id() as i32);
  // ... assertions that might panic — guard Drop cleans up ...
  let output = guard.wait_with_output().expect("wait");

## Depends On

- pn-54b92ef0 (ChildGuard in shutdown crate)
- pn-d8ca99b3 (SGF_TEST_NO_SETSID so children stay killable)

## Required Tests

Integration test — panic_does_not_leak_child_tree:
1. Spawn sgf with mock ralph via ChildGuard::spawn
2. Wait for ready (ready file)
3. Record sgf PID and mock ralph PID (mock script writes its PID to a file)
4. catch_unwind to drop guard during simulated panic
5. Verify BOTH sgf and mock ralph PIDs are dead

In crates/ralph/src/main.rs:433-435, the ding_watcher() function spawns afplay without waiting on the Child handle:

  let _ = Command::new("afplay").arg("/System/Library/Sounds/Blow.aiff").spawn();

The Child is immediately dropped. Since Rust's Child has no Drop impl, the afplay process detaches and runs orphaned. Over many ding notifications, these accumulate.

## Fix

Block on the child:
  if let Ok(mut child) = Command::new("afplay").arg("...").spawn() {
      let _ = child.wait();
  }

afplay for a system sound takes <1 second. The ding_watcher thread polls every 100ms and dings are infrequent, so blocking is acceptable.

No dedicated tests needed — trivial one-line fix.
